This feature of Piraha˜ is itself very rare (see Corbett 2000:50). There may be no other language that lacks the grammatical category of number.

There are three words in Piraha˜ that are easy to confuse with numerals because they can be translated as numerals in some of their uses:4 ho´ i ‘small size or amount’, hoı´ ‘somewhat larger size or amount’, and ba´ a gi so lit. ‘cause to come together’ (loosely ‘many’). Some examples which show how Piraha˜ expresses what in other cultures would be numerical concepts are as follows:

