Neither the declarative (35) nor the interrogative (36) form of recursive possession is acceptable. No more than one possessor per noun phrase is ever allowed. Removing one of the possessors in either sentence makes it grammatical. A cultural observation here is, I believe, important for understanding this restriction. Every Piraha˜ knows every other Piraha˜ , and they add the knowledge of newborns very quickly. Therefore one level of possessor is all that is ever needed. If further identiﬁcation is called for, say, in the case of a foreign family, then an extra phrase is juxtaposed:

